    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-4-3-1-sols">
        <title><m>\S 4.3</m>: Diagonalization (Solutions)</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Diagonalization</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Recall that <m>A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
    1 \amp 2 \\
    2 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}\right]
    </m>
                        has eigenvectors <m>\vvec_1=\twovec{1}{1}</m> and
    <m>\vvec_2 = \twovec{-1}{1}</m> and associated eigenvalues
    <m>\lambda_1=3</m> and <m>\lambda_2=-1</m>.
                        <image source="diag-intro.png">
                            <shortdescription>Eigenvectors of A on the left, and the transformation of the eigenvectors
                                after multiplications by A.
                            </shortdescription>
                        </image>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We see that <m>A</m> scales vectors in the coordinates of <m>\{\vvec_1 , \vvec_2\}</m> by scaling the
                            first coordinate by a factor of <m>3</m>, and the second coordinate by a factor of <m>1</m>. In what 
                            way is <m>A</m> related to the matrix that does the same thing to standard coordinates,
                            <m>D = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>?
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Preview Activity 4.3.1</title>
                    <introduction>
	<p> In this preview activity, we will review some familiar
	properties about matrix multiplication that appear in this
	section.</p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
	  <p>
	    Remember that matrix-vector multiplication constructs
	    linear combinations of the columns of the matrix.  For
	    instance, if
	    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}
	    \avec_1 \amp \avec_2 \end{bmatrix}</m>, express the
	    product <m>A\twovec2{-3}</m> in terms of <m>\avec_1</m>
	    and <m>\avec_2</m>.
	  </p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p>
	    <m>A\twovec{2}{-3} = 2\avec_1 - 3\avec_2</m>.
	  </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p>
	    What is the product <m>A\twovec40</m> in terms of
	    <m>\avec_1</m> and <m>\avec_2</m>?
	  </p>
        </statement>
       
        <solution>
	  <p>
	    <m>A\twovec40 = 4\avec_1</m>.
	  </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p>
	    Next, remember how matrix-matrix multiplication is
	    defined.  Suppose that we have matrices <m>A</m> and
	    <m>B</m> and that <m>B = \begin{bmatrix}
	    \bvec_1 \amp \bvec_2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.  How can we
	    express the matrix product <m>AB</m> in terms of the
	    columns of <m>B</m>?
	  </p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p>
	    <m>AB = \begin{bmatrix}
	    A\bvec_1 \amp A\bvec_2
	    \end{bmatrix}</m>.
	  </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p>
	    Suppose that <m>A</m> is a matrix having eigenvectors
	    <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m> with associated
	    eigenvalues <m>\lambda_1 = 4</m> and <m>\lambda_2 =
	    -1</m>.  Express the product <m>A(2\vvec_1+3\vvec_2)</m>
	    in terms of <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m>.
	  </p>
        </statement>
       
        <solution>
	  <p>
	    <m>A(2\vvec_1 + 3\vvec_2) = 8\vvec_1 - 3\vvec_2</m>.
	  </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p>
	    Suppose that <m>A</m> is the matrix from the previous
	    part and that <m>P=\begin{bmatrix} \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2
	    \end{bmatrix}</m>.  What is the matrix product
	    <me>
	      AP = A\begin{bmatrix}
	      \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2
	      \end{bmatrix}?
	    </me>
	  </p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p>
	    <m>AP =
	    \begin{bmatrix}
	    A\vvec_1 \amp A\vvec_2
	    \end{bmatrix}
	    =
	    \begin{bmatrix}
	    4\vvec_1 \amp -\vvec_2
	    \end{bmatrix}
	    </m>.
	  </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
                    
                    
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Diagonalization</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Suppose <m>A</m> is <m>n \times n</m> and <m>\{\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \dots, \vvec_n\}</m> is a basis 
                            consisting of eigenvectors of <m>A</m> with associated eigenvalues <m>\lambda_1, \lambda_2 ,\dots, \lambda_n</m>.
                            If 
                            <me>
                               
P = \begin{bmatrix}
\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \cdots \amp \vvec_n
\end{bmatrix},
                                
                                \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,

                                D = \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_1 \amp 0 \amp \ldots \amp 0 \\
0 \amp \lambda_2 \amp \ldots \amp 0 \\
\vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp 0 \\
0 \amp 0 \amp \ldots \amp \lambda_n \\
\end{array}\right]
                            </me>, then 
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>AP = PD</m>. Since <m>A</m> is invertible, <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m>. This shows us precisely how 
                            <m>A</m> can be framed as "similar" to the diagonal matrix <m>D</m>: the matrix <m>A</m> acts on a vector
                            in standard coordinates in the same way as <m>D</m> acts acts on that vector written 
                            in the coordinates of the columns of <m>P</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We say that <m>A</m> is <term>diagonalizable</term> if there is a diagonal matrix <m>D</m> and invertible 
                            matrix <m>P</m> such that <m>A = PDP^{-1}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Fact: Diagonalization</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            An <m>n \times n </m> matrix <m>A</m> is diagonalizable exactly when 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            there is a basis of <m>\R^n</m> consisting of eigenvectors of <m>A</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Diagonalizable</title>
                    
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Suppose <m>A= PDP^{-1}</m>, where 
                            <me>
                            D = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
2 \amp 0 \\
0 \amp -2 \\
\end{array}\right],\qquad
P = 
\left[\begin{array}{rr}
1 \amp 1 \\
1 \amp 2 \\
\end{array}\right].
                            </me>

                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            See <url href="https://understandinglinearalgebra.org/sec-eigen-diag.html#sec-eigen-diag-3-13">Example 4.3.8 </url>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

